        info: {
            description: `
            Set in <strong>New York City during spring break of 2009</strong>, Roaming follows three Canadian first-year university students—Zoe, Dani, and Fiona—as they navigate five days in the Big Apple. Childhood best friends Zoe and Dani, now freshmen at different colleges, reunite for the trip they have always dreamed of. But Dani unexpectedly brings along her Montreal roommate, Fiona, an unapologetically confident art student whose magnetic, world-weary coolness immediately attracts Zoe. As the trio roams through iconic New York locations—the Metropolitan Museum of Art, Grand Central Terminal, Central Park, Coney Island—an unexpected romance blossoms between Zoe and Fiona, throwing Zoe and Dani's long-term friendship off-balance.

            The title Roaming is a deliberate play on words: the protagonists are physically roaming through New York, but they are also worried about the roaming charges they might incur on their cellphones in 2009, a liminal time when most people didn't have smartphones and data was prohibitively expensive. More metaphorically, "roaming" represents exploring new relationships, new expressions of self, and the messy, exhilarating, and often painful process of stepping out of childhood and into adulthood.

            The book was a monumental critical success. It won three <Strong>2024 Eisner Awards: Best Graphic Album</strong>, with Mariko winning <strong>Best Writer</strong> and Jillian winning <strong>Best Penciller/Inker</strong>. It was a finalist for the <strong>2024 Lambda Literary Awards</strong> and tied for the top graphic novel in Publishers Weekly's annual critics poll. It has been described as "an observant, richly illustrated story about outgrowing old relationships and growing into new ones", "a masterpiece", and "a future classic". The book has drawn comparisons to the works of Tillie Walden, Jul Maroh, and Laura Gao.
        `,
            plot: `
            <i>Roaming</i> unfolds over five days in spring 2009. The following outlines the major story beats and character dynamics.
            
            <strong>Part One: The Reunion and the Unexpected Guest:</strong> The story opens with a cinematic, joyous airport scene as Zoe and Dani reunite in New York City. Zoe, a Queen's University student, waits for her old friend Dani at the airport, eager for the trip they have been planning for months. But their reunion is unexpectedly upended: Dani has brought along her Montreal roommate, Fiona. Fiona is white, femme, and a self-appointed judge of what's cool in New York. She smokes, dismisses tourist activities as boring, and presents herself as world-wise and effortlessly confident.


            <strong>Part Two: The City and the Growing Tension:</strong> The trio checks into a hostel and begins exploring the city. Dani wants to do classic tourist things: eat pizza, see Coney Island, Times Square, and the Statue of Liberty. But Fiona scoffs at the mere mention of tourism, insisting they see "real" neighborhoods instead. Zoe, caught in the middle but unable to deny Fiona's magnetic coolness, agrees.

            Small cracks in Zoe and Dani's long-term friendship become visible early on. Zoe's new buzzcut shocks Dani, who later asks if Zoe has "always hated her hair". While Fiona fully embraces Zoe's new look, Dani reminisces over their senior semi-formal photos when Zoe had long hair, to which Fiona responds that Zoe's hair "looks a million times better shaved".


            <strong>Part Three: The Romance and the Fracture:</strong> A romance begins to blossom between Zoe and Fiona. Zoe's building infatuation with Fiona leads her to tolerate things she normally wouldn't, including Fiona's occasional casual racism and belittling of Dani. Dani, feeling increasingly left out, becomes frustrated and blurts out: "I wanted to come here and hang out with my best friend, but you're like... not even you anymore". The trio navigates a late-aughts New York with spotty cell service and tenuous personal connections.


            <strong>Part Four: The Confrontation and the Aftermath:</strong> The tension reaches a breaking point in an inevitable blowup. Zoe realizes how far astray she has gone in her quest for Fiona's approval. Dani, meanwhile, is not purely a victim; she exhibits passive-aggressive behavior and has fallen for Fiona's dubious charm enough to bring her on the trip in the first place. The novel's ending has been described by some critics as "vaguely unsatisfying", but the relationships themselves are "a masterclass in subtlety". The characters' internal monologues are excellent, and the representation of female sexuality is unabashed. Each character is painfully alive and real—"not necessarily likable," but that's what keeps things interesting.
        `,
            reviewsReceptions: `
            <strong>A Slice-of-Life Masterpiece for the New Adult Years</strong>
            Mariko Tamaki's writing in Roaming is a masterclass in subtle, character-driven storytelling. Unlike many graphic novels that rely on high-concept plots or dramatic twists, Roaming finds its power in small, zoomed-in moments. As one review notes, the Tamakis possess "a talent for crafting stories of immense substance out of small, zoomed-in moments". Because of their specificity, these micro-stories speak to a much broader macro-story: "Almost everyone knows a Fiona, has been a Zoe or has become frustrated with the hesitance of the Dani in their life".
            
            
            <strong>The Complexity of Friendship and the Messiness of Adulthood</strong>
            The characters in Roaming "defy easy categorization". Fiona is self-interested and occasionally cruel, but New York and "the messy freedom of adulthood seems to expose something unpleasant in all three characters". The book refuses to offer easy judgments or simple resolutions. As the ROOM Magazine review observes, the Tamakis "subtly cue readers to this theme in the opening pages" and weave together "an ever-changing, dynamic cityscape with characters who are also constantly evolving and struggling to embrace every version of themselves—past, present, and future".


            <strong>Authentic Dialogue and Relatable Characters</strong>
            Mariko's "keen ear for realistic dialogue" is frequently praised. The characters and their experiences "hit hard because of how incredibly real they feel". One review notes that "despite the intrinsic brevity of the format, Dani, Fiona and Zoe are fully fleshed out". The dialogue is so natural that it makes readers want to hold their breath—as when Zoe says, "The best thing about having a body... it knows what to do. Some things it just knows".


            <strong>The 2009 Setting as a Liminal Space</strong>
            The decision to set the book in 2009 is deliberate and effective. It is "a liminal time when most people didn't have smart phones, and cell data was prohibitively expensive". In this context, "roaming isn't just a setting on a cell phone. It also represents exploring a new city, new relationships, and new expressions of self". The limited technology forces the characters to be more present with each other—and more vulnerable.


            <strong>Minor Criticisms</strong>
            While the book is overwhelmingly praised, some critics have noted that the ending "falls short, with a vaguely unsatisfying conclusion". Others have noted that the characters are "not necessarily always likable". However, even these criticisms are typically accompanied by praise for the book's subtlety, its gorgeous artwork, and its unparalleled insight into being young and at a tipping point in life.
        `
        },
