        info: {
            description: `
            Set in a <strong>San Francisco</strong> suburb during the late <strong>1980s and early 1990s</strong> (specifically 1989 to 1992), Smile follows <strong>Raina</strong>, an 11-year-old sixth grader who has a seemingly ordinary life—until the night she trips and falls, severely injuring her two front teeth. What follows is a long and frustrating journey through a gauntlet of dental procedures: on-again, off-again braces, surgery, embarrassing headgear, and even a retainer with fake teeth attached. The memoir chronicles Raina's experience from sixth grade through tenth grade, as she navigates not only the physical pain and social embarrassment of her dental trauma, but also the universal challenges of adolescence: shifting friendships, self-esteem issues, bullying, and the search for identity.

            Smile was a monumental critical and commercial success. It became a <strong>#1 New York Times Bestseller</strong> and won the <strong>2011 Eisner Award for Best Publication for Teens</strong>. It was also a <strong>Boston Globe-Horn Book Honor Book</strong> and received five starred reviews. Kirkus Reviews called it "Irresistible, funny, and touching", while The New York Times Book Review noted that "it hits home partly because there is nothing else out there like it". The book has been translated into multiple languages, has sold millions of copies worldwide, and has become a staple of middle-grade classrooms and libraries. It is widely regarded as one of the most important and influential graphic novels of the 21st century, credited with popularizing the graphic memoir format for young readers and inspiring a generation of new comics creators.
        `,
            plot: `
            <i>Smile</i> is a chronological, episodic memoir that follows Raina's journey from sixth grade through tenth grade. The following outlines the major story beats and character arcs.

            <strong>Part One: The Accident and the Aftermath:</strong> The story opens with <strong>Raina</strong>, a normal 11-year-old sixth grader who enjoys Girl Scouts, hanging out with friends, and the ordinary pleasures of childhood. One night after a Girl Scouts meeting, she trips and falls, <strong>knocking out her two front teeth</strong>. The dentist puts them back in and says they should heal properly—but they don't. Raina is plunged into a seemingly endless series of dental procedures: root canals, braces, surgery, embarrassing headgear, and a retainer with fake teeth attached. The physical pain is compounded by the social humiliation: Raina is self-conscious about her appearance, and her peers sometimes mock her.


            <strong>Part Two: The Shifting Friendships and the Search for Identity:</strong> As Raina navigates middle school and high school, her friendships shift and change. Some friends become less supportive as Raina's social challenges increase. She struggles with self-esteem issues and anxiety about fitting in. The dental drama serves as a metaphor for the larger challenges of adolescence: the feeling of being different, the fear of being labeled, and the search for one's own identity. Raina's relationship with her younger sister Amara is also explored—Amara initially teases Raina about her braces, but their relationship evolves over time. The book addresses themes of anxiety and bullying.


            <strong>Part Three: The Recovery and the Resolution:</strong> By the end of the book, Raina's teeth are finally repaired. But more importantly, she has grown as a person. She learns to prioritize her passions—particularly her love of art—over her appearance. The story concludes on a hopeful note: Raina has survived the ordeal and emerged stronger, more self-assured, and more resilient. As the Scholastic summary puts it, "One thing is for certain, the experience will change her—and life can only get better from here".
        `,
            reviewsReceptions: `
            <strong>An Authentic and Relatable Voice</strong>
            Raina Telgemeier's writing in Smile is praised for its honesty, humor, and emotional depth. The narrative voice is authentic and relatable, capturing the anxieties, embarrassments, and small triumphs of adolescence with remarkable specificity. As Kirkus Reviews noted, the book is "Irresistible, funny, and touching". Telgemeier does not shy away from the painful or embarrassing moments—the awkwardness of wearing headgear, the sting of being mocked by peers, the loneliness of feeling different—but she balances these with warmth, humor, and a sense of hope.
            
            
            <strong>The Power of the Graphic Memoir Format</strong>
            Smile is often credited with popularizing the graphic memoir format for young readers. The combination of words and images allows Telgemeier to convey complex emotions with remarkable economy. As The New York Times Book Review noted, "it hits home partly because there is nothing else out there like it". The visual medium makes the story accessible to reluctant readers while still offering depth and emotional resonance for more advanced readers.


            <strong>The Power of the Graphic Memoir Format</strong>
            Smile is often credited with popularizing the graphic memoir format for young readers. The combination of words and images allows Telgemeier to convey complex emotions with remarkable economy. As The New York Times Book Review noted, "it hits home partly because there is nothing else out there like it". The visual medium makes the story accessible to reluctant readers while still offering depth and emotional resonance for more advanced readers.


            <strong>Themes of Resilience and Self-Discovery</strong>
            At its core, Smile is a story about resilience and self-discovery. Raina's dental trauma is a metaphor for the larger challenges of adolescence: the feeling of being different, the fear of being judged, and the struggle to find one's place in the world. The book explores themes of shame and pride, childhood and youth, and the importance of prioritizing one's passions over one's appearance. It also addresses anxiety and bullying in a way that is accessible and reassuring for young readers.


            <strong>Minor Criticisms</strong>
            While the book is overwhelmingly praised, some critics have noted that the plot can feel somewhat predictable at times. Others have expressed a desire for the book to delve more deeply into Raina's family relationships. However, these criticisms are minor and are vastly outweighed by the book's critical consensus as a masterpiece of the graphic memoir genre.
        `
        },
        link: "https://www.hoopladigital.com/comic/smile-a-graphic-novel-raina-telgemeier/16129580"
